“My first memory of literature is my mother reading me excerpts from African mythology,” says Ketty Valenico, the founder of the Afro-Brazilian bookstore @livrariafricanidades. 🌍📚

Ketty started Livraria Africanidades as a way to honor Black narratives and authors and has since built a physical and digital community of like-minded women to help contribute to her vision for a more inclusive Latin America. 

Her story is part of our new series, togetHER: a celebration of the spirit, resilience and creative endeavors of women-owned businesses and how they cultivate strength and power from community. Watch to see her journey unfold and discover more stories from the series via the link in bio.

*Trigger warning: domestic violence.* “It is a privilege to do this work every day,” says Lovern Gordon, the founder of @lovelifenowfound, a foundation dedicated to raising awareness around the issue of domestic violence. 

Lovern, who is a survivor herself, transformed her trauma into strength when she started the Love Life Now Foundation on Instagram as a way to connect and help other survivors. “Having women around me that support me — that in and of itself is a huge deal.”

Lovern’s story is part of our new series, togetHER: a celebration of the spirit, resilience and creative endeavors of women-owned businesses and how they cultivate strength and power from community. Watch to see her journey unfold and discover more stories from the series via the link in bio.

When she left her home in Nigeria for San Francisco, creative entrepreneur Simileoluwa Adebajo had no idea she’d end up opening a restaurant that pays homage to her grandmother’s cooking. She created Eko Kitchen (@ekokitchensf) in 2018 as a way to combat homesickness for her home country, but the restaurant quickly became a place that fed and nourished the souls of an entire community. ❤️🍴 

With support from friends, family and local business owners, Simileoluwa pivoted her business model during the pandemic by providing meals for the homeless and those in need. “In 2020, I realized how important my digital community was. The small words of encouragement really kept me going.” 💡

Simileoluwa’s story is part of our new series, togetHER: a celebration of the spirit, resilience and creative endeavors of women-owned businesses and how they cultivate strength and power from community. Watch to see her journey unfold and discover more stories from the series via the link in bio.

If you’ve watched some (or all) of @Buzzfeedtasty’s mouthwatering recipe videos, you might’ve seen food and video producer @thedessertsnob busy in the kitchen making it “fancy.” 😉 

In episode 5 of In My Saves, we’re going behind the scenes and into Rie’s Saves to see how she organizes her content and keeps tabs on inspiration for future videos. ❤️

7 years ago, @framebridge set out on a mission to offer high quality, affordable and fast custom framing — which is exactly what they did. 🖼

Today, the direct-to-consumer brand continues to reach new customers through their Shop on Instagram. An additional e-commerce entry point, the Framebridge shop has become a go-to destination. 🛍️

“Our customers are able to transition from discovery to checkout with less friction,” says Jeannie O'Reilly, Director of Acquisition and Retention. 🛒 

For the holidays, the brand is prioritizing best-sellers, quick-ship gifts and a special ornament made just for the season. “As always, we’ll be sure to update our product photography to include festive images and holiday specific UGC,” says Jeannie. 🎁

For more inspiration on how to get started with Instagram Shopping, checkout the link in our bio. 🤓 #GetYourShopOn

40% of recently surveyed Instagram users say they’re more likely to purchase from brands that post light-hearted or humorous content. So go ahead: share the silly, the weird and the wild. 🐶🛹 🤪

Looking for inspiration? Tap the link in bio to browse ideas for on-brand content that entertains your audience and keeps them coming back for more.

🎨 by @sylviaboomeryang 

Source: Instagram Trends Research Study (Facebook-commissioned survey of 4,500 Instagram active users ages 18–50 in AU, BR, DE, FR, IN, JP, KR, UK, US) by Ipsos, Nov 2020. N=500 for each market, Instagram active users are weekly IG users who create contents on the platform based on stated survey data.

node.text:
When it came to opening their own store, Collin James and Brandon Veloria, who run the New York City-based vintage store @jamesveloria, got started by selling their vintage clothes on Instagram. 🛒 👗

“We use Instagram to showcase vintage designer clothing on our colorful community of friends and collaborators, showing that fashion is for everyone!,” says Brandon. Now, they’ve opened their first brick-and-mortar store in the heart of Chinatown. 💖

In celebration of Pride, we asked Colin and Brandon to share some of their favorite LGBTQ+ owned businesses who’s feeds are full of inspiring to build community and engage your customers. Check out our latest Guide to see their picks. 🏳️‍🌈
